First, what is a MessageChannel?

A MessageChannel is simply an interface through which Spring passes Message<?> objects.

public interface MessageChannel {
    boolean send(Message<?> message);
}

Instead of directly calling your controller,
 Spring passes messages through these channels so interceptors, security, logging,
 and the broker can all participate.


                    CLIENT
                       │
                 WebSocket/STOMP
                       │
                       ▼
         +---------------------------+
         | clientInboundChannel      |
         +---------------------------+
                  │
                  │
      ChannelInterceptor runs here
       (JWT Authentication)
                  │
                  ▼
       @MessageMapping Controller
                  │
                  ▼
           brokerChannel
                  │
                  ▼
       Simple Broker / RabbitMQ
                  │
                  ▼
       clientOutboundChannel
                  │
                  ▼
                 CLIENT











1. clientInboundChannel

This carries every STOMP frame sent by the client to the server.

Examples:

CONNECT
SUBSCRIBE
SEND
UNSUBSCRIBE
DISCONNECT

Suppose the client sends

CONNECT
Authorization: Bearer eyJhb...

The flow becomes

Client
   │
   ▼
clientInboundChannel
   │
   ▼
Your ChannelInterceptor
   │
   ▼
Spring

This is why your interceptor is registered like this:

@Override
public void configureClientInboundChannel(ChannelRegistration registration) {
    registration.interceptors(stompAuthInterceptor);
}

Your interceptor receives every incoming frame.

Example:

CONNECT

↓

clientInboundChannel

↓

preSend()

↓

Authenticate JWT

↓

Continue

Another example:

SEND
destination:/app/chat
body:Hello

↓

clientInboundChannel

↓

preSend()

↓

Controller
Why authentication is done here

Because the client is sending something.

Spring gives you the message before it reaches your controller.

You can:

Reject invalid JWT
Reject unauthorized users
Log activity
Rate limit
Modify headers
2. clientOutboundChannel

This channel is the opposite direction.

It carries messages from the server to the client.

Suppose User A sends

Hello

Your controller executes

messagingTemplate.convertAndSend(
        "/topic/room1",
        message
);

Now Spring must send the message back to subscribed users.

Flow:

Controller
      │
      ▼
Simple Broker
      │
      ▼
clientOutboundChannel
      │
      ▼
WebSocket
      │
      ▼
Clients

So outbound messages look like

MESSAGE
destination:/topic/room1

Hello

Notice this is not coming from the client.

It is going to the client.

Therefore authentication is already done.

You generally don't verify JWT here.

Typical uses of outbound interceptors:

Logging
Encrypting payloads
Modifying headers
Metrics

Not authentication.

3. brokerChannel

This one confuses most beginners.

It is completely internal.

The client never touches it.

Imagine your controller:

@MessageMapping("/chat")
public void send(MessageRequest request) {

    messagingTemplate.convertAndSend(
            "/topic/room1",
            request
    );
}

Internally, Spring does something like

Controller
      │
      ▼
brokerChannel
      │
      ▼
SimpleBroker
      │
      ▼
clientOutboundChannel

The broker channel is simply how Spring components communicate with the message broker.

It never receives WebSocket traffic directly.

Complete Example

Suppose User A sends

CONNECT

Flow:

Client
   │
   ▼
clientInboundChannel
   │
   ▼
Interceptor
   │
Authenticate JWT
   │
Store Authentication
   │
Connected

Now User A sends

SEND
destination:/app/chat

Hello

Flow:

Client
   │
   ▼
clientInboundChannel
   │
   ▼
Interceptor
   │
(no authentication now)
   │
   ▼
@MessageMapping

Controller:

messagingTemplate.convertAndSend(
        "/topic/room1",
        msg
);

Now

Controller
   │
   ▼
brokerChannel
   │
   ▼
Simple Broker
   │
   ▼
clientOutboundChannel
   │
   ▼
User B
User C
User D
Summary



| Channel                   | Direction                  | Carries                                                            | Common Use                                                        |
| ------------------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **clientInboundChannel**  | Client → Server            | `CONNECT`, `SEND`, `SUBSCRIBE`, `UNSUBSCRIBE`, `DISCONNECT`        | Authentication, authorization, validation, rate limiting, logging |
| **brokerChannel**         | Internal (Server → Broker) | Messages passed from controllers/application to the message broker | Internal routing between Spring and the broker                    |
| **clientOutboundChannel** | Server → Client            | `MESSAGE`, `ERROR`, `RECEIPT`, etc.                                | Logging, metrics, header modification before delivery             |
















The three channels involved

Spring's STOMP setup has three channels, but you only care about one for this:

clientInboundChannel — messages coming FROM client TO server (CONNECT, SUBSCRIBE, SEND). This is where you intercept for auth.
clientOutboundChannel — messages going FROM server TO client (broadcasts). Not relevant here.
brokerChannel — internal server-side routing. Not relevant here.




